<button class="accordion">What is food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food safety is used as a scientific discipline that describes handling, preparation, and storage of food in ways that prevent foodborne illness. The occurrence of two or more cases of a similar illness resulting from the ingestion of a common food is known as a foodborne disease outbreak.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is meant by food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food safety refers to the proper handling, cooking, and preservation of food in order to protect people from foodborne illnesses caused by microbes such as bacteria, fungi, parasites, and viruses.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is food safety important?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food safety awareness and consumer education on food safety will help strengthen enforcement of food standards, improve hygienic practices, and prevent foodborne illnesses.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 5 food safety rules?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>5 Food Safety Rules:</p>
<li> Rule 1: Wash hands between steps</li>
<li> Rule 2: Sanitise work surfaces</li>
<li> Rule 3: Use separate cutting boards for raw meats, vegetables and produce, and cooked foods</li>
<li> Rule 4: Cook foods to safe temperatures</li>
<li> Rule 5: Keep hot foods hot and cold foods cold.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are food safety and food quality?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food Safety refers to practices and conditions that preserve the quality of food to prevent contamination and foodborne illnesses during preparation, handling and storage.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 10 rules for safe food practice?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>These are the 10 rules for safe food practices:</p>
<li> Choose foods processed for safety</li>
<li> Cook food thoroughly</li>
<li> Eat cooked foods immediately</li>
<li> Store cooked foods carefully</li>
<li> Reheat cooked foods thoroughly</li>
<li> Avoid contact between raw foods and cooked foods</li>
<li> Wash hands repeatedly</li>
<li> Keep all kitchen surfaces meticulously clean</li>
<li> Protect foods from insects, rodents, and other animals</li>
<li> Use safe water.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is a food hazard?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A food safety hazard is anything present in food with the potential to harm the consumer, either by causing illness or injury. Food safety hazards can be biological, chemical, or a physical object.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the importance of food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food safety is essential as it helps to protect the consumer from the risk of foodborne illnesses. It also helps to prevent consumers from risks of health-related conditions such as allergies and even death.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 4 types of food hazards?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>There are 4 primary categories of food safety hazards to consider:</p>
<li> Biological</li>
<li> Chemical</li>
<li> Physical</li>
<li> Allergenic.</li>
<p>Understanding the risks associated with each can dramatically reduce the potential of foodborne illness.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What causes food contamination?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>An infectious organism, such as bacteria, viruses and parasites or their toxins are the most common causes of food poisoning. Infectious organisms or their toxins can contaminate food at any point of processing or production. Contamination can also occur at home if food is incorrectly handled or cooked.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the basic food hygiene rules?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food Hygiene Guidelines:</p>
<li> Wash hands before and after handling food, after breaks, after the toilet.</li>
<li> Encourage 'customers' to wash their hands before eating.</li>
<li> Do not sneeze or cough near food.</li>
<li> Do not smoke or eat in any kitchen areas.</li>
<li> Put clothes, jackets, bags in a separate area away from cooking areas.</li>
<li> Tie back or cover long hair.</li>
<li> Wear clean clothing.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the hazards of food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A food safety hazard refers to any agent with the potential to cause adverse health consequences for consumers. Food hazards may be biological, chemical, physical, allergenic, nutritional and/or biotechnology-related.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the food safety guidelines?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>In every step of food preparation, follow the four guidelines to keep food safe:</p>
<li> Clean - wash hands and surfaces often</li>
<li> Separate - do not cross-contaminate</li>
<li> Cook - cook to proper temperatures, and check with a food thermometer</li>
<li> Chill - refrigerate promptly.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 4 C's of good food hygiene?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A Care Worker's Guide to the 4 C's of Food Hygiene Safety. In the health and social care sector, the four C's are especially important for food hygiene safety. These are as follows:</p>
<li> Cleaning</li>
<li> Cooking</li>
<li> Cross-contamination</li>
<li> Chilling.</li>
<p>All come into play during the food handling process and must be implemented properly at all times.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the principles of food hygiene?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>According to the WHO, the five key principles of food hygiene include:</p>
<li> Prevent contaminating food with pathogens spreading from people, pets, and pests.</li>
<li> Separate raw and cooked foods to prevent contaminating the cooked foods.</li>
<li> Cook foods for the appropriate length of time and at the appropriate temperature to kill pathogens.</li>
<li> Store food at the proper temperature.</li>
<li> Use safe water and safe raw materials.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between food safety and food hygiene?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food Safety covers all aspects of ensuring that food is safe for a person to eat. In contrast, food hygiene specifically concerns foodborne illnesses, which arise because of primarily bacterial contaminants, chemicals and physical hazards.</p>
</div>
