<button class="accordion">Who is responsible for food safety in the UK?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) is responsible for food safety and food hygiene in England, Wales and Northern Ireland. It works with local authorities to enforce food safety regulations, ensuring the standards are met.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do I need a food hygiene certificate in the UK?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes, food hygiene training is a legal requirement for anyone that works with food. Food law states that all food handlers receive appropriate food safety and food hygiene training and supervision in the workplace. The Food Safety Act 1990 is the legal framework for all food legislation in Britain.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 3 types of food contamination?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Here are the three types of contaminants:</p>
<li> Biological: Examples include bacteria, viruses, parasites, fungi, and toxins from plants, mushrooms, and seafood. </li>
<li> Physical: Examples include foreign objects such as dirt, broken glass, metal staples, and bones.</li>
<li> Chemical: Examples include cleaners, sanitisers, and polishes.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the types of hazard?</button>
