<li> Biological - This includes bacteria, viruses, insects, plants, birds, animals, and humans.</li>
<li> Chemical - This depends on the physical, chemical and toxic properties of the chemical compounds.</li>
<li> Ergonomic - These are repetitive movements, improper set up of workstation, and other related things.</li>
</div>

<button class="accordion">Who governs food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The FDA is charged with protecting consumers against impure, unsafe, and fraudulently labelled products. FDA, through its Center for Food Safety and Applied Nutrition (CFSAN), regulates foods other than meat, poultry, and egg products regulated by FSIS.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are three things you should avoid when preparing food?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>To prevent the spread of bacteria while you're preparing food:</p>
<li> Always wash your hands with warm water and soap before preparing any food.</li>
<li> Wash your hands after handling raw meat, poultry, fish, or egg products.</li>
<li> Keep raw meats and their juices away from other foods in the refrigerator and on countertops.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is proper food storage?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Proper food storage helps maintain food quality by retaining flavour, colour, texture and nutrients while reducing the chance of contracting a foodborne illness.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the challenges to food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The challenges to food safety include:</p>
<li> Changes in food production and supply</li>
<li> Changes in the environment leading to food contamination</li>
<li> Better detection of multistate outbreaks</li>
<li> New and emerging bacteria, toxins, and antibiotic resistance.</li>
</div>
