</div>
<button class="accordion">Who regulates the food industry in the UK?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) is responsible for food safety and food hygiene in England, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is hair in food a health hazard?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The FDA has received no reports of people getting ill from ingesting hair found in food. The truth is, you might have eaten hair today.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What does a food safety inspector do?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>They may inspect live animals and carcasses at a slaughterhouse or examine food imports at a port for mislabeling other food safety issues. Inspectors report violations to the appropriate regulatory agency and are responsible for ensuring that foods are suitable for human food consumption.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do and don'ts of food preparation?</button>
<div class="panel">
<li> Don't rinse meat before cooking.</li>
<li> Don't rinse eggs.</li>
<li> Do wash produce.</li>
<li> Don't soak the meat in salt water to remove bacteria.</li>
<li> Do wash your hands to prevent cross-contamination after handling raw meat.</li>
<li> Do wash countertops and sinks with hot, soapy water to prevent cross-contamination from raw meat or poultry juices.</li>
<li> Do throw away meat packaging.</li>
<li> Don't reuse any cooking utensils that have been used on raw meats.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are unsafe foods?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Unsafe foodstuffs can contain many types of harmful bacteria, viruses, parasites or chemicals. Examples include undercooked meat, fruits and vegetables contaminated with faeces and shellfish containing marine toxins.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How does food become unsafe?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Foodborne illness happens when food is not kept at the correct temperature, and a germ is allowed to multiply. Besides, chemical spills increase the chance of foodborne illnesses.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How do we maintain food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>In every step of food preparation, follow the four guidelines to keep food safe:</p>
<li> Clean - Wash hands and surfaces often.</li>
<li> Separate - Do not cross-contaminate.</li>
<li> Cook - Cook to proper temperatures, checking with a food thermometer.</li>
<li> Chill - Refrigerate promptly.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the four core practices for safe food handling?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Cross-contamination plays a part in spreading the bacteria. When handling raw meat, poultry, seafood and eggs, keep these foods and their juices away from ready-to-eat foods. Always start with a clean scene by washing your hands with warm water and soap. Also, do not forget to wash cutting boards, dishes, countertops and utensils with hot soapy water.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What can poor food hygiene cause?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>If pathogens such as bacteria or viruses are exposed to food and go on to be consumed, victims can become unwell several hours or even days later. Consequences of poor food hygiene can result in serious cases of food poisoning and hospitalisation for those exposed.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the safety rules?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>No person shall be permitted to remain on the premises while their ability to work is so affected by alcohol, drugs or other substance. It may endanger the health or safety of any other person.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is food quality and safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food safety refers to all those hazards, whether chronic or acute, that may make food harmful to the consumer's health. Quality includes all other attributes that influence a product's value to the consumer.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How long does it take to get a food safety certificate?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The course and test generally take about 2 hours to complete. However, it could take longer if you wish to review important course information to be better prepared for the exam and your work in foodservice. </p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is food quality and safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Many states require staff in the food and beverage industry to receive adequate training on how to safely handle and prepare food. These employees include food handlers, chefs, servers, and managers. Some states require food establishments to have at least one certified Food Safety Manager or Food Protection Manager.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is a food hygiene certificate?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>This is a basic food hygiene course with approved certificate, which ensures that anyone working in an environment where food is cooked, prepared or handled complies fully with current UK legislation.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Who is responsible for food safety?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The food industry is responsible for producing safe food. Government agencies are responsible for setting food safety standards, conducting inspections, ensuring that standards are met, and maintaining a strong enforcement program to deal with those who do not comply with standards.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Who is responsible for food safety in a restaurant?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A food business' owner has a legal responsibility to its customers' welfare to protect their health and safety. A business owner must:</p>
<li> Notify the local council with details of their food business.</li>
<li> Ensure the business complies with the Food Standards Code.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How long does food hygiene certificate last in the UK?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Food hygiene certificates do not expire. However, some employers, such as the NHS require them to renew the certificate every 12 months. It is a recognised industry practice for them to be renewed every three years so that food handlers can keep up to date with the latest legislation.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do I need a food hygiene certificate to sell cakes?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>You do not need a food hygiene certificate to make and sell food for charity events. However, you must ensure to follow proper food handling and storage to prevent illnesses and/or contamination.</p>
</div>
